<!-- [1,2,3,4~0,2,2,0~1,0,3,0~0,1,0,4] -->=20
<p>The determinant is (using the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/alge=
bra/matrix-calculator.html">Matrix Calculator</a>):</p>=20
<p>1(2(3=C3=974-0=C3=970)-2(0=C3=974-0=C3=971)+0(0=C3=970-3=C3=971))-2(0(3=
=C3=974-0=C3=970)-2(1=C3=974-0=C3=970)+0(1=C3=970-3=C3=970))+3(0(0=C3=974-0=
=C3=971)-2(1=C3=974-0=C3=970)+0(1=C3=971-0=C3=970))-4(0(0=C3=970-3=C3=971)-=
2(1=C3=970-3=C3=970)+2(1=C3=971-0=C3=970)) =3D <b>8</b></p>=20
<p class=3D"large">The determinant is <b>non-zero</b> so they must all be <=
b>linearly independent</b>.</p>=20
<p>Also:</p>=20
<div class=3D"so">it is full rank, and the rank is <b>4</b></div>
<div class=3D"so">it is a basis for 4D space: using these 4 vectors we can =
span all of 4D space</div>
<p>A great example where mathematics can tell us something that we can't ea=
sily imagine.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Other Properties</h2>=20

<p>The rank can't be larger than the smallest dimension of the matrix.</p>=
=20

<div class=3D"example">=20

<h3>Example: for a 2=C3=974 matrix the rank can't be larger than 2</h3>=20

</div>=20

<p>When the rank equals the smallest dimension it is called "full rank", a =
smaller  rank is called "rank deficient".</p>=20
<p>The rank is at least 1, except for a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.c=
om/algebra/matrix-types.html">zero matrix</a> (a matrix made of all zeros) =
whose rank is 0.</p>=20
